Tesfaye cites [[Michael Jackson]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and [[R. Kelly]] as his main musical inspirations.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Scott |first=Damien |title=The Weeknd: Kiss And Tell (2013 Cover Story) |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614024520/http://ca.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |archive-date=June 14, 2015 |date=July 15, 2013 |website=[[Complex Networks]]}}</ref> He has attributed Jackson's music as key in spurring him to be a singer, referencing the lyrics to "[[Dirty Diana]]" as an example.<ref name="Fantasy3"/> His high-flying vocal style was influenced by Ethiopian singers such as [[Aster Aweke]].<ref name="Fantasy3"/> He grew up listening to a variety of music genres, including [[Soul music|soul]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[funk]], [[indie rock]], and [[post-punk]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberts |first=Randall |title=Review: Abel Tesfaye, a.k.a. The Weeknd, has hall smoldering |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-xpm-2012-dec-17-la-et-ms-weeknd-review-20121217-story.html |url-status=live |date=December 17, 2012 | url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223950/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-xpm-2012-dec-17-la-et-ms-weeknd-review-20121217-story.html |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> Tesfaye is heavily influenced by [[1980s in music|1980s music]], and credits the video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]'' (2002) for "opening my eyes" to the music of that era.<ref>{{Cite web|date=November 24, 2021|title=The Weeknd: 'Grand Theft Auto: Vice City' "opened my eyes to '80s music"|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-grand-theft-auto-vice-city-80s-music-3103875|access-date=February 16, 2022|website=NME|language=en-GB|archive-date=February 16, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220216043000/https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-grand-theft-auto-vice-city-80s-music-3103875|url-status=live}}</ref> "I've always had an admiration for the era before I was born", he said in an interview for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. "You can hear it as far back as my first mixtape that the '80s – [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Cocteau Twins]] – play such a huge role in my sound."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=April 1, 2020 |title=The Weeknd on Being the First Artist to Top These 5 Charts At Once: 'It Feels Like a Huge Blessing' (Exclusive) |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9348979/the-weeknd-interview-historic-chart-domination-exclusive/ |access-date=May 18, 2021 |archive-date=May 29, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210529115936/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9348979/the-weeknd-interview-historic-chart-domination-exclusive/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Tesfaye has named [[Deftones]] as one of his influences during the making of ''[[House of Balloons]]'', ''[[Thursday (album)|Thursday]]'' and ''[[Echoes of Silence]]''.<ref name="Metal Sucks genres">{{Cite web|date=August 22, 2021|title=The Weeknd Says Deftones Inspired His Music|url=https://www.metalsucks.net/2021/08/22/the-weeknd-says-deftones-inspired-his-music/|access-date=January 8, 2022|website=MetalSucks|language=en|archive-date=January 7, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220107183847/https://www.metalsucks.net/2021/08/22/the-weeknd-says-deftones-inspired-his-music/|url-status=live}}</ref> He has also cited [[Lana Del Rey]],<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mistry|first=Anupa|date=August 31, 2015|title=The Dark Knight Returns: A Conversation With the Weeknd|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/interview/9711-the-dark-knight-returns-a-conversation-with-the-weeknd/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223955/https://pitchfork.com/features/interview/9711-the-dark-knight-returns-a-conversation-with-the-weeknd/?page=1|archive-date=January 7, 2021|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref> [[David Bowie]],<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Reed|first=Ryan|date=November 2, 2016|title=The Weeknd Talks David Bowie, Prince Influences on New Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-weeknd-talks-david-bowie-prince-influences-on-new-album-w448191|url-status=live|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223944/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-talks-david-bowie-prince-influences-on-new-album-122216/|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> [[the Smiths]], [[Bad Brains]], [[Talking Heads]], [[DeBarge]],<ref name="bruce">{{Cite web|last=Slingerland|first=Calum|date=February 6, 2016|title=The Weeknd's New Album Is Inspired by Bad Brains, Talking Heads and the Smiths|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknds_new_album_is_inspired_by_bad_brains_talking_heads_and_the_smiths|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225173258/https://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknds_new_album_is_inspired_by_bad_brains_talking_heads_and_the_smiths|archive-date=February 25, 2021|website=[[Exclaim!]]}}</ref> [[50 Cent]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]],<ref>{{Cite web|last=Schwadron|first=Eli|date=December 14, 2016|title=50 Cent and Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album Read More: 50 Cent, Wu-Tang Are Influences on The Weeknd's New 'Starboy' Album|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/50-cent-wu-tang-influenced-the-weeknds-starboy-album/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325061023/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/50-cent-wu-tang-influenced-the-weeknds-starboy-album/|archive-date=March 25, 2017|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last1=Exposito|first1=Suzy|last2=Harris|first2=Keith|last3=Mistry|first3=Anupa|last4=Murray|first4=Nick|last5=Spanos|first5=Brittany|date=October 21, 2015|title=12 Great Songs That Wouldn't Exist Without the Weeknd|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/12-great-songs-that-wouldnt-exist-without-the-weeknd-20151021/drake-hold-on-were-going-home-2013-20151021|url-status=live|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223941/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/12-great-songs-that-wouldnt-exist-without-the-weeknd-160938/drake-hold-on-were-going-home-2013-154472/|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> and [[Eminem]] as influences and inspirations.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W0b6RGdLqTM|title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Crashed Jay Z on 'Renegade,' Talks "The Hills" Remix|date=November 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223953/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W0b6RGdLqTM|archive-date=January 7, 2021|url-status=live|work=Southpawer|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=November 25, 2016|title=The Weeknd Says Eminem Destroyed 'The Hills' Remix and Jay Z on 'Renegade'|url=http://www.southpawer.com/2016/11/25/the-weeknd-eminem-jay-z-renegade-the-hills-interview/|url-status=usurped|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218123555/http://www.southpawer.com/2016/11/25/the-weeknd-eminem-jay-z-renegade-the-hills-interview/|archive-date=February 18, 2019|website=Southpawer}}</ref> When [[Daft Punk]] announced their split in 2021, Tesfaye praised them during an interview with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', saying: "Those guys are one of the reasons I make music, so I can't even compare them to other people..."<ref>{{Cite news|date=February 23, 2021|title=The Weeknd Recalls Working With Daft Punk: 'They're One of the Reasons I Make Music'|newspaper=Variety |url=https://variety.com/2021/music/news/the-weeknd-daft-punk-starboy-1234913297/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226001913/https://variety.com/2021/music/news/the-weeknd-daft-punk-starboy-1234913297/|archive-date=February 26, 2021 |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem }}</ref>

=== Production and songwriting ===
Tesfaye's songs are "built around a fogged, [[crepuscular]] production",<ref name="Hoby">{{Cite news |last=Hoby |first=Hermione |title=The Weeknd: Sounds and sensibility |work=[[The Guardian]] | author-link=Hermione Hoby |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |url-status=live |date=November 8, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002143549/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |archive-date=October 2, 2013}}</ref> and feature slow [[tempo]]s,<ref name="Trilogy" /> rumbling bass, and forlorn echoes.<ref name="Mistry" /> His music incorporates [[Sampling (music)|samples]] that are unconventional in R&B production, including [[Punk rock|punk]], [[shoegaze]], [[dream pop]] and [[alternative rock]].<ref name="thing">{{Cite news |last=Considine |first=J. D. |author-link=J. D. Considine |title=How The Weeknd became R&B's next big thing |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |location=Toronto |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/how-the-weeknd-became-rbs-next-big-thing/article5370329/ |url-status=live |date=November 17, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223955/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/how-the-weeknd-became-rbs-next-big-thing/article5370329/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> [[Marc Hogan]] of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' says that Tesfaye's samples tend "to draw from [[Rockism and poptimism|rock critic-approved]] sources, though generally ones that already share elements of his sexual menace", sampling artists such as [[Beach House]], Siouxsie and the Banshees and [[Aaliyah]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hogan |first=Marc | author-link=Marc Hogan |title=The Weeknd Imbues 'Enemy' With the Smiths' Seductive Power |url=https://www.spin.com/2012/10/the-weeknd-enemy-the-smiths/ |url-status=live |location=[[New York City]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223927/https://www.spin.com/2012/10/the-weeknd-enemy-the-smiths/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |date=October 26, 2012 | website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref> Tesfaye worked mostly with producers [[Illangelo]] and [[Doc McKinney]], whom Ian Cohen of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' credits with developing "a state-of-the-art [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] template" with the artist.<ref name="Trilogy">{{Cite web |last=Cohen |first=Ian |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17280-the-trilogy/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223948/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17280-the-trilogy/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |date=November 13, 2012 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref> In concert, Tesfaye reappropriates his digitized productions with a [[Suite (music)|suite]]-like [[arena rock]] aesthetic.<ref name="Mistry" />

His emotional, plaintive lyrics often express feelings of hurt and deal with subject matter such as sex,<ref name="Hoby" /> drugs, and partying; this is seen especially in ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' and ''House of Balloons''.<ref name="Mistry" /> [[Hermione Hoby]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' characterizes Tesfaye's songs as "narcotised-[[slow jam]]s" and delineates their message as "partying is an existential experience, sex is fraught with alienation, and everything registers as unreal and unsettling."<ref name="Hoby" /> Paul MacInnes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that he views Tesfaye's three mixtapes as "a rough trajectory of party, after-party and [[hangover]]."<ref>{{Cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |title=The Weeknd: Trilogy – review |at=section G2, p. 23 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/15/the-weeknd-trilogy-review |url-status=live |date=November 15, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030193412/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/15/the-weeknd-trilogy-review |archive-date=October 30, 2013}}</ref> Anupa Mistry of the ''Toronto Standard'' observes throughout his mixtapes a "cast of supine, stoned zombie-women... whose legs willingly part after being plied with substances and who morph into threats only when [he is] [[Comedown (drugs)|coming down]] and feeling vulnerable."<ref name="Mistry" /> Tesfaye has stated that by singing vulgar, ignorant lyrics in an elegant, sexy way, he is "paying homage to R Kelly, and even Prince to a certain extent."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scott |first=Damien |title=The Weeknd: Kiss And Tell (2013 Cover Story) |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110063852/https://www.complex.com/music/2013/07/weeknd-interview-cover-story |archive-date=November 10, 2015 |date=July 15, 2013 |publisher=Complex}}</ref>

=== Voice and music style ===
Tesfaye often sings in a [[falsetto]] register.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Robbins |first=Winston |date=December 7, 2011 |title=Rookie of the Year: The Weeknd |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/12/rookie-of-the-year-2011/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112021827/http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/12/rookie-of-the-year-2011/ |archive-date=January 12, 2013 |website=[[Consequence (publication)|Consequence]]}}</ref> [[J. D. Considine]] finds his singing's "[[Tremolo|tremulous]] quality" similar to Michael Jackson, but writes that he eschews Jackson's "strong basis in the [[blues]]" for a more [[Arabic music|Arabic]]-influenced [[melisma]].<ref name="thing" /> Tesfaye possesses a wide light-lyric [[tenor]] vocal range, which spans over three octaves. His vocal range reaches its extreme low at the bass F (F<sub>2</sub>), and its peak high at the tenor G{{sharp}} (G{{sharp}}<sub>5</sub>), with a natural [[tessitura]] within the upper fourth octave.<ref>{{Cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wr-K4d9BbzM | title=(HD) The Weeknd's Vocal Range: D2 - C6 | work=Prettiboimico | via=[[YouTube]] | date=January 5, 2013 | access-date=May 23, 2021 | archive-date=May 23, 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523145647/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wr-K4d9BbzM | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="range">{{Cite news | url=https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/is-the-weeknd-good-singer-vocal-range/ | title=Is The Weeknd a good singer, and what is his vocal range? | first=Kyle | last=Macdonald | work=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] | date=March 22, 2021 | access-date=May 23, 2021 | archive-date=May 23, 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523145638/https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/is-the-weeknd-good-singer-vocal-range/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Tesfaye often makes use of his [[head voice]] to build resonance to belt out strong high notes within the fifth octave.<ref name="range" /> Tesfaye's vocals have a recognizable [[Music of Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] characteristic. Hannah Giogis of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' notes that "his trademark [[vibrato]], the characteristically pained whine that pervades much of Tesfaye's music, draws from a long Ethiopian musical legacy of tortured pining. Imbuing our voices with the shaky pain of loss—romantic or otherwise—is a hallmark of Ethiopian musical tradition. Tesfaye, with his [[staccato]] wails and aching nostalgia, is a young, North American addition to a dynasty of [[melodrama]]tic Ethiopian singers."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giorgis |first1=Hannah |title=The Weeknd's East African Roots |url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/793-the-weeknds-east-african-roots/ |work=Pitchfork |date=June 11, 2015 |access-date=March 4, 2022 |archive-date=January 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130004835/https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/793-the-weeknds-east-african-roots/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2023, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked the Weeknd at number 110 on its list of the 200 Greatest Singers of All Time.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=January 1, 2023|title=The 200 Greatest Singers of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/best-singers-all-time-1234642307/the-weeknd-12-1234643026/|access-date=May 24, 2023|magazine=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|archive-date=May 24, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524221408/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/best-singers-all-time-1234642307/the-weeknd-12-1234643026/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Tesfaye's discography spans [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Dance music|dance]], [[Alternative rock|alternative]] and [[New wave music|new wave]] genres.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=October 1, 2020|title=Is the Weeknd Pop, R&B or Hip-Hop? Why the Distinction Matters at the Grammys|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-grammys-pop-hip-hop-category-1234789560/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=Variety|language=en-US|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215133202/https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-grammys-pop-hip-hop-category-1234789560/|url-status=live}}</ref> His work is generally categorized as [[alternative R&B]], due to his contributions in broadening the genre's musical palette to incorporate [[Indie music|indie]] and [[Electronic music|electronic]] styles.<ref name="Preview">{{Cite news|date=February 13, 2016|title=Grammys 2016 Preview: The Weeknd, D'Angelo and More Soulful Singers Nominated for Best R&B Song and Best Urban Contemporary Album|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6813596/grammys-2016-preview-best-r-and-b-song-best-urban-contemporary-album-nominees-the-weeknd-dangelo-more|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223949/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6813596/grammys-2016-preview-best-r-and-b-song-best-urban-contemporary-album-nominees-the-weeknd-dangelo-more|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref name="allmusicbio">{{Cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|title=The Weeknd – Music Biography, Credits and Discography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223953/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-weeknd-mn0002674162|archive-date=January 7, 2021|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|mode=cs2}}</ref> Mistry writes that he "will be obsequiously praised as the future of R&B music—because Tesfaye is a black singer, not because he's making quantifiable, canonical R&B."<ref name="Mistry" /> Tesfaye shared his thoughts on the primary label during an interview with ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' in 2015, stating: "Alternative R&B is in my soul. It's not going anywhere. When I put out songs from ''House of Balloons'' in 2010, people said I made R&B cool again. I'm assuming that's when the label was created. I feel honored that a good part of today's music is inspired by it, consciously or subconsciously. The only way I could have done that was to be ambitious and grand."<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=The Rise of the Weeknd: 'I Want to Make Pop Cool Again'|url=https://time.com/4011859/the-weeknd-interview-beauty-behind-themadness/|access-date=February 15, 2022|magazine=Time|language=en|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215203439/https://time.com/4011859/the-weeknd-interview-beauty-behind-themadness/|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesfaye's first three mixtapes; ''House of Balloons'', ''Thursday'' and ''Echoes of Silence'', are alternative R&B projects that draw on dream pop, post-punk and [[trip hop]], amongst others.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Conteh|first=Mankaprr|date=March 22, 2021|title=The Weeknd's 'The Party & the After Party' Paved the Way for our Genre-less Future|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/house-of-balloons-the-weeknd-best-track-1145332/|access-date=December 9, 2021|magazine=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|quote=The Weeknd's massive career was built on a foundation of dream pop and post-punk.|archive-date=December 9, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211209055045/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/house-of-balloons-the-weeknd-best-track-1145332/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Scarano|first=Ross|date=November 21, 2019|title=Songs That Defined the Decade: The Weeknd's 'House of Balloons/Glass Table Girls'|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-house-of-balloons-songs-that-defined-the-decade-8544245/|access-date=February 15, 2022|magazine=Billboard|language=en-US|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215180545/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-house-of-balloons-songs-that-defined-the-decade-8544245/|url-status=live}}</ref> His debut studio album ''[[Kiss Land]]'' is categorized as R&B and [[dark wave]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Charlton|first=Lauretta|title=How the Weeknd Went From Underground Anonymity to Superstar in 5 Years, According to His Collaborators|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/08/the-weeknd-collaborators-chronicle-his-rise.html|access-date=December 9, 2021|website=Vulture|date=September 7, 2015|language=en-us|quote=It sounded like he was merging goth, dark-wave, and R&B with a punk-rock sensibility. It sounded like something completely new.|archive-date=December 9, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211209055039/https://www.vulture.com/2015/08/the-weeknd-collaborators-chronicle-his-rise.html|url-status=live}}</ref> His next three albums, ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]'', ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]'' and ''After Hours'', are considered R&B and pop; with ''Starboy'' utilizing heavy [[Trap music|trap]] influences,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Berry|first=Peter A.|title=The Weeknd Shines Brightly on 'Starboy' - XXL|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/the-weeknd-starboy-album-review/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=XXL Mag|date=December 5, 2016|language=en|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215133205/https://www.xxlmag.com/the-weeknd-starboy-album-review/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Feeney|first=Nolan|date=November 29, 2016|title=The Weeknd's Starboy: EW Review|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/11/29/weeknd-starboy-ew-review/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=EW.com|language=en|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215133202/https://ew.com/article/2016/11/29/weeknd-starboy-ew-review/|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''After Hours'' drawing on new wave and dream pop influences.<ref name="Consequence AH">{{Cite news |last=McDuffie |first=Candace |date=March 24, 2020 |title=The Weeknd – After Hours |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-the-weeknd-after-hours/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324135956/https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-the-weeknd-after-hours/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |website=[[Consequence (publication)|Consequence]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Herrera|first=Isabella|date=March 24, 2020|title=The Weeknd: After Hours|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-weeknd-after-hours/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=Pitchfork|language=en-US|archive-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324073404/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-weeknd-after-hours/|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesfaye's fifth studio album ''[[Dawn FM]]'' explores [[dance-pop]] and [[synth-pop]] genres.<ref>{{Cite web|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=January 7, 2022|title=Review: The Weeknd's 'Dawn FM' Is An Art-Damaged Dancefloor Opus Inspired By Pandemic Purgatory|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2171899/the-weeknd-dawn-fm/reviews/premature-evaluation/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=Stereogum|language=en|archive-date=January 8, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220108204719/https://www.stereogum.com/2171899/the-weeknd-dawn-fm/reviews/premature-evaluation/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Matt|date=January 7, 2022|title=Dawn FM Is The Weeknd's Grandest Synth-Pop Gesture and a Thoughtful Rumination on Mortality|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/the-weeknd/dawn-fm-album-review/|access-date=February 15, 2022|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|language=en|archive-date=January 12, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112024904/https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/the-weeknd/dawn-fm-album-review/|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Controversies ==

=== Plagiarism allegations ===
In December 2015, Tesfaye was sued by Cutting Edge Music, which alleged that the [[bassline]] for "[[The Hills (song)|The Hills]]" had been taken from a composition featured in the score for the 2013 [[science fiction]] film ''[[The Machine (2013 film)|The Machine]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |date=December 9, 2015 |title=The Weeknd Sued over 'The Hills' |website=[[TMZ]] |url=https://www.tmz.com/2015/12/09/the-weeknd-the-hills-lawsuit/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224110/https://www.tmz.com/2015/12/09/the-weeknd-the-hills-lawsuit/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> One of the producers of the song was alleged to have sent a private [[Twitter]] message to Tom Raybould, the composer of the film's score, to tell him about the sample.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Renshaw |first=David |date=December 10, 2015 |title=The Weeknd sued over alleged similarities between 'The Hills' and sci-fi movie score |work=[[NME]] |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-18-1203899 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224138/https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-18-1203899 |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In September 2018, Tesfaye and [[Daft Punk]] were sued for allegedly stealing the rhythm for "[[Starboy (song)|Starboy]]" from Ethiopian poet and singer-songwriter Yasminah.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 18, 2018 |title=The Weeknd and Daft Punk Sued for Stealing 'Starboy' |website=[[TMZ]] |url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/09/18/the-weeknd-daft-punk-lawsuit-starboy-stolen/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224051/https://www.tmz.com/2018/09/18/the-weeknd-daft-punk-lawsuit-starboy-stolen/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> Tesfaye denied the allegations.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 18, 2019 |title=The Weeknd Denies Stealing "Starboy" Beat From Somali-American Singer |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-denies-stealing-starboy-beat-from-somali-american-singer-news.80542.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224110/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-denies-stealing-starboy-beat-from-somali-american-singer-news.80542.html |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In April 2019, Tesfaye was sued by British trio William Smith, Brian Clover, and Scott McCulloch, who accused Tesfaye of [[copyright infringement]] from plagiarising their song "I Need to Love" in order to create his song "[[A Lonely Night]]". They sought $150,000 from Tesfaye and [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]]. In August 2019, the lawsuit was dismissed via [[summary judgment]] with the option to amend, with the court ruling that they had failed to show that Tesfaye or anyone else involved in making "A Lonely Night" had access to their song or that the works were substantially similar.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brittain |first=Blake |date=September 8, 2020 |title=The Weeknd's Copyright Win Fails to Justify Attorneys' Fees |publisher=[[Bloomberg Industry Group]] |url=https://convergenceapi.bna.com/ContentItem/ArticlePublic/253904988000000002/298944 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210401003732/https://convergenceapi.bna.com/ContentItem/ArticlePublic/253904988000000002/298944?itemGuid=b4f14fef-d221-4cbb-9c99-7b96a557a9d7&dashboardId=0&alertGuid=7dba4c60-b2f0-4b22-81cb-a45dff01addb&emailaddress=%24%24%24EMAILADDRESS%24%24%24 |archive-date=April 1, 2021}}</ref> In September 2019, the plaintiffs filed an amended claim based on secondary infringement, which is still in litigation.<ref>{{Cite news |last=O'Connor |first=Roisin |date=April 4, 2019 |title=The Weeknd sued by British songwriters over 'A Lonely Night' plagiarism accusations |website=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-weeknd-a-lonely-night-copied-plagiarism-lawsuit-belly-rapper-a8854351.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224103/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/weeknd-lonely-night-copied-plagiarism-lawsuit-belly-rapper-a8854351.html |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Malt |first=Andy |date=November 11, 2019 |title=The Weeknd has move to dismiss song-theft lawsuit dismissed denied |website=[[Complete Music Update]] |url=https://completemusicupdate.com/article/the-weeknd-has-move-to-dismiss-song-theft-lawsuit-dismissed-denied/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224125/https://completemusicupdate.com/article/the-weeknd-has-move-to-dismiss-song-theft-lawsuit-dismissed-denied/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In February 2020, Tesfaye and [[Kendrick Lamar]] were sued by the now-defunct indie band [[Yeasayer]], claiming that "[[Pray for Me (The Weeknd and Kendrick Lamar song)|Pray for Me]]" includes an unauthorized sample of their song "Sunrise".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=February 24, 2020 |title=Yeasayer Sue the Weeknd, Kendrick Lamar Over 'Black Panther' Song |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/yeasayer-the-weeknd-kendrick-lamar-black-panther-song-lawsuit-957606/ |access-date=July 20, 2021 |archive-date=July 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210720093908/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/yeasayer-the-weeknd-kendrick-lamar-black-panther-song-lawsuit-957606/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that year, Yeasayer voluntarily dismissed their lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Strauss |first=Matthew |date=July 10, 2020 |title=Yeasayer Drop Lawsuit Against the Weeknd |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/yeasayer-drop-lawsuit-against-the-weeknd/ |access-date=July 20, 2021 |archive-date=September 17, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210917101716/https://pitchfork.com/news/yeasayer-drop-lawsuit-against-the-weeknd/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2021, Tesfaye, [[Nicolas Jaar|Nicolás Jaar]], and [[Frank Dukes]] were sued for copyright infringement by producers Suniel Fox and Henry Strange, protesting that "[[Call Out My Name]]" is "strikingly [or] substantially similar, if not identical" to their 2015 track "Vibeking".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bloom |first=Madison |date=September 22, 2021 |title=The Weeknd and Nicolás Jaar Sued for Copyright Infringement Over "Call Out My Name" |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-and-nicolas-jaar-sued-for-copyright-infringement-over-call-out-my-name/ |access-date= |website=Pitchfork |language=en-US |archive-date=October 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028214607/https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-and-nicolas-jaar-sued-for-copyright-infringement-over-call-out-my-name/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Robinson |first=Kristin |date=September 22, 2021 |title=The Weeknd Accused of Plagiarizing 2018 Song 'Call Out My Name' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/legal-and-management/9633774/the-weeknd-copyright-lawsuit-call-out-my-name |magazine=Billboard |language=en |access-date= |archive-date=October 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028025152/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/legal-and-management/9633774/the-weeknd-copyright-lawsuit-call-out-my-name/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Allegations of homophobic lyrics ===
In January 2019, Tesfaye was criticized for some of the lyrics in his and [[Gesaffelstein]]'s single "[[Lost in the Fire]]". The second verse of the song, with the lines "You said you might be [[Women who have sex with women|into girls]], said you're going through a phase / Keeping your heart safe / Well, baby, you can bring a friend / She can [[Facesitting|ride on top your face]] / While I fuck you [[Heterosexuality|straight]]", were accused of being [[Homophobia|homophobic]], fetishizing [[bisexuality]], and perpetuating the falsehood that a person who identifies as being part of the [[LGBT community|LGBTQ+ community]] can be "[[Conversion therapy|turned straight]]".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Whitehead |first=Joanna |date=January 14, 2019 |title=The Weeknd's lyrics were homophobic – who cares if it's 'sensitive' to point that out? |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/weeknd-lost-fire-homophobia-snowflakes-metoo-music-lgbtq-abuse-a8727666.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220620/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/weeknd-lost-fire-homophobia-snowflakes-metoo-music-lgbtq-abuse-a8727666.html |archive-date=June 20, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Dodgson |first=Lindsay |date=January 14, 2019 |title=People are calling out The Weeknd for a 'homophobic' new song that suggests lesbianism is a 'phase' and he can 'f— a girl straight' |work=[[Business Insider]] |url=https://www.insider.com/the-weeknd-called-out-for-homophobic-lyrics-lost-in-the-fire-2019-1 |access-date=July 15, 2021 |archive-date=October 29, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231029160607/https://www.insider.com/the-weeknd-called-out-for-homophobic-lyrics-lost-in-the-fire-2019-1 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tesfaye subtly addressed the controversy in the song "[[Snowchild]]" from ''After Hours'', with the lines "Every month another accusation / Only thing I'm phobic of is failing".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=July 22, 2020 |title=Watch The Weeknd's Wild, Semi-Autobiographical Anime Video for 'Snowchild' |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-snowchild-anime-video-watch-1234713552/ |access-date=November 4, 2021 |website=Variety |language=en-US |archive-date=November 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104161455/https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-snowchild-anime-video-watch-1234713552/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=July 22, 2020 |title=Watch The Weeknd face up to his past in animated 'Snowchild' video |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-the-weeknd-face-up-to-his-past-in-animated-snowchild-video-2713136 |access-date=November 4, 2021 |website=NME |language=en-GB |archive-date=November 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104161454/https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-the-weeknd-face-up-to-his-past-in-animated-snowchild-video-2713136 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== ''The Idol'' allegations ===
On March 1, 2023, ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' released a lengthy exposé on the working conditions and set life of the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[The Idol (TV series)|The Idol]]'', a series in which Tesfaye stars, co-created and co-wrote alongside [[Sam Levinson]]. The series received significant controversy for its graphic depiction of sexual content, which critics labeled "[[torture porn]]". The series was originally directed by [[Amy Seimetz]] who suddenly "exited with roughly 80 percent of the six-episode series finished". The series saw a major creative overhaul, as it was reported that Tesfaye felt the show had too much of a "female perspective". Over 14 crew members alleged a toxic work environment with one adding "What I signed up for was a dark satire of fame and the fame model in the 21st century..." however, "It went from satire to the thing it was satirizing." Sources alleged that Seimetz's approach to the story was scrapped and the show became "like any [[rape fantasy]] that any toxic man would have in the show — and then the woman comes back for more because it makes her music better".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-features/the-idol-hbo-next-euphoria-torture-porn-the-weeknd-sam-levinson-lily-rose-depp-blackpink-jennie-1234688754/|title= 'The Idol': How HBO's Next 'Euphoria' Became Twisted 'Torture Porn'|website= [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|date= March 2023|accessdate= June 19, 2023|archive-date= March 1, 2023|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230301220933/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-features/the-idol-hbo-next-euphoria-torture-porn-the-weeknd-sam-levinson-lily-rose-depp-blackpink-jennie-1234688754/|url-status= live}}</ref>

In response to the allegations, Tesfaye mocked the reporting on his Twitter account, posting a clip of the characters in the show discussing the magazine saying, "''Rolling Stone''? Aren't they a little irrelevant?". Tesfaye posted the comment in the caption: "@''Rolling Stone'' did we upset you?".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2023-03-02/the-weeknd-rolling-stone-the-icon|title= The Weekend mocked online for his Rolling Stone response|website= [[Los Angeles Times]]|date= March 3, 2023|accessdate= June 19, 2023|archive-date= June 18, 2023|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230618131211/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2023-03-02/the-weeknd-rolling-stone-the-icon|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.indiewire.com/features/general/the-weeknd-the-idol-clip-rolling-stone-1234814937/|title= The Weeknd Posts 'The Idol' Clip Mocking Rolling Stone After Report of On-Set Dysfunction|website= [[IndieWire]]|date= March 2023|accessdate= June 19, 2023|archive-date= June 19, 2023|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230619235015/https://www.indiewire.com/features/general/the-weeknd-the-idol-clip-rolling-stone-1234814937/|url-status= live}}</ref> Tesfaye's response received widespread criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.newsweek.com/weeknd-idol-hbo-set-chaos-report-allegations-reaction-1785005|title= The Weeknd Mocked After Hitting Back at 'Idol' Set Drama Report: 'Bad Look'|website= Newsweek|date= March 2, 2023|accessdate= June 19, 2023|archive-date= June 19, 2023|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230619105818/https://www.newsweek.com/weeknd-idol-hbo-set-chaos-report-allegations-reaction-1785005|url-status= live}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', he continued to dismiss the reporting, saying that logistical difficulties with Seimetz's schedule and production timelines, as well as a desire not to rush his first show, propelled the overhaul.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2023/05/the-weeknd-remade-pop-music-will-the-idol-remake-the-weeknd|title= The Weeknd Remade Pop Music. Will The Idol Remake The Weeknd?|magazine= Vanity Fair|date= May 16, 2023|accessdate= June 27, 2023|archive-date= June 18, 2023|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230618173531/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2023/05/the-weeknd-remade-pop-music-will-the-idol-remake-the-weeknd|url-status= live}}</ref>

==Other ventures==

=== Acting ===
Tesfaye is a [[Cinephilia|cinephile]], and has made numerous movie references in his music videos and teasers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Movie References in The Weeknd's After Hours You Never Noticed|url=https://www.moviefone.com/2021/02/16/movie-references-in-the-weeknds-after-hours-you-never-noticed/|access-date=June 30, 2021|website=www.moviefone.com|language=en|archive-date=March 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240310195100/https://www.moviefone.com/news/movie-references-in-the-weeknds-after-hours-you-never-noticed/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Willman|first=Chris|date=September 10, 2019|title=How the Weeknd Came to Play Himself in the Safdie Brothers' Berserk 'Uncut Gems'|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/the-weeknd-acting-safdie-brothers-uncut-gems-1203329975/|access-date=July 1, 2021|website=Variety|language=en-US|archive-date=February 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210208020551/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/the-weeknd-acting-safdie-brothers-uncut-gems-1203329975/|url-status=live}}</ref> On August 30, 2019, during the [[Telluride Film Festival]], he made his acting debut in the film ''[[Uncut Gems]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gwee |first=Karen |date=September 10, 2019 |title=The Weeknd recorded music with Oneohtrix Point Never intended for 'Uncut Gems' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/film/weeknd-recorded-music-oneohtrix-point-never-intended-uncut-gems-2546398 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929014540/https://www.nme.com/news/film/weeknd-recorded-music-oneohtrix-point-never-intended-uncut-gems-2546398 |archive-date=September 29, 2019 |website=[[NME]]}}</ref>

On March 7, 2020, during his third appearance as a musical guest on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', he starred in the skit "On The Couch" with actors [[Kenan Thompson]] and [[Chris Redd]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=March 9, 2020|title=SNL's 'On the Couch' Song Is Brutal and Hilariously Relatable|url=https://www.fatherly.com/news/snls-on-the-couch-song-is-brutal-and-hilariously-relatable/|access-date=June 30, 2021|website=Fatherly|language=en-US|archive-date=July 9, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709185806/https://www.fatherly.com/news/snls-on-the-couch-song-is-brutal-and-hilariously-relatable/|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 4, he co-wrote and starred in an episode of ''[[American Dad!]].''<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|date=April 1, 2020|title=American Dad!' Gets TBS Return Date – Watch The Promo|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/american-dad-premiere-date-trailer-seth-macfarlane-the-weeknd-tbs-1202897703/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223933/https://deadline.com/2020/04/american-dad-premiere-date-trailer-seth-macfarlane-the-weeknd-tbs-1202897703/|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In July, he voiced three characters during the 200th episode of ''[[Robot Chicken]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|date=July 28, 2020|title=The Weeknd makes cameo appearance on 'Robot Chicken'|url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/the-weeknd-makes-cameo-appearance-on-robot-chicken-2716813|access-date=June 30, 2021|website=NME|language=en-GB}}</ref>

On June 29, 2021, Tesfaye announced that he would be co-creating, co-writing, executive producing and starring in the [[HBO]] television drama series ''[[The Idol (TV series)|The Idol]]'', alongside his producing partner Reza Fahim and ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]'' creator [[Sam Levinson]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Weeknd to Co-Create and Star in New HBO Series The Idol|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-to-co-create-and-star-in-new-hbo-series-the-idol/|access-date=June 30, 2021|website=Pitchfork|date=June 29, 2021|language=en-US}}</ref> On March 20, 2022, Tesfaye voiced two characters during an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Dailey |first=Hannah |date=March 7, 2022 |title=The Weeknd Announces 'Dream' Cameo on 'The Simpsons': 'Proud of This One' |url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/tv-film/the-weeknd-the-simpsons-cameo-1235040261/ |access-date=March 16, 2022 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref>

In 2023, it was announced that Tesfaye is co-writing a film with [[Trey Edward Shults]], who is attached to direct; Tesfaye is also set to star in the film, alongside [[Jenna Ortega]] and [[Barry Keoghan]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kroll |first1=Justin |title=The Weeknd, Jenna Ortega And Barry Keoghan To Star In New Film Based On Original Idea From The Weeknd With Trey Edward Shults Directing |url=https://deadline.com/2023/02/the-weeknd-jenna-ortega-barry-keoghan-trey-edward-shults-1235274366/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 28, 2023 |access-date=August 1, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/features/general/the-weeknd-jenna-ortega-trey-edward-shults-1234814337/|title=The Weeknd, 'Waves' Director Trey Edward Shults' to Co-Write New Film|last=Chapman|first=Wilson|date=February 28, 2023|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=November 16, 2023}}</ref>

=== Business ===
In 2013, Tesfaye collaborated with [[condom]] company ONE to give away limited-edition condoms at his shows during the Kiss Land Fall Tour.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Battan |first=Carrie |date=September 26, 2013 |title=The Weeknd Giving Away Kiss Land Condoms |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/52443-the-weeknd-giving-away-kiss-land-condoms/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224014/https://pitchfork.com/news/52443-the-weeknd-giving-away-kiss-land-condoms/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hudson |first=Alex |date=September 26, 2013 |title=The Weeknd Gets His Own 'Kiss Land' Condoms |work=[[Exclaim!]] |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/weeknd_gets_his_own_kiss_land_condoms}}</ref> In November 2015, he partnered with [[Vaporizer (inhalation device)|electronic vaporizer]] company [[Pax Labs]] to release a limited edition vaporizer.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Keating |first=Lauren |date=November 4, 2015 |title=The Weeknd Launches A Vape That Plays His Hit Single 'The Hills' As You Smoke |work=Tech Times |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/103135/20151104/weeknd-launches-vape-plays-hit-single-hills-smoke.htm |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224001/https://www.techtimes.com/articles/103135/20151104/weeknd-launches-vape-plays-hit-single-hills-smoke.htm |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=November 13, 2015 |title=The Weeknd Gets Limited Version of Pax 2 Vaporizer |url=https://porhomme.com/2015/11/the-weeknd-gets-limited-version-of-pax-2-vaporizer/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223952/http://porhomme.com/2015/11/the-weeknd-gets-limited-version-of-pax-2-vaporizer/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=Por Homme |publisher=Pausr Media LLC}}</ref> He also collaborated with fashion designer [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]] for an apparel collection.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hasse |first=Lemola |date=November 14, 2015 |title=HYPEBEAST Exclusive: WANGXO Apparel Collection |url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/11/wangxo-apparel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224043/https://hypebeast.com/2015/11/wangxo-apparel |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=Hypebeast}}</ref> In 2016, Tesfaye became a creative collaborator and [[Brand ambassador|global brand ambassador]] for the clothing brand [[Puma (brand)|Puma]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mench |first=Chris |date=September 29, 2016 |title=The Weeknd Partners With Puma as New Creative Collaborator and Ambassador |url=https://www.complex.com/style/2016/09/the-weeknd-partners-puma-creative-collaborator-ambassador |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223947/https://www.complex.com/style/2016/09/the-weeknd-partners-puma-creative-collaborator-ambassador |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[Complex Networks]]}}</ref> With the partnership, he released numerous capsule collections and hosted several [[pop-up retail]] stores.<ref name="Pop-Up">{{Cite news |last=Tucker |first=Alexa |date=May 4, 2017 |title=Where Are The Weeknd's Pop-Up Shops? If You Live in One Of These Eight Cities, You're in Luck |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-are-the-weeknds-pop-up-shops-if-you-live-in-one-of-these-eight-cities-youre-in-luck-55779 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223950/https://www.bustle.com/p/where-are-the-weeknds-pop-up-shops-if-you-live-in-one-of-these-eight-cities-youre-in-luck-55779 |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=November 22, 2017 |title=A Closer Look at The Weeknd x PUMA XO Collection Launch in NYC |url=https://hypebeast.com/2017/11/he-weeknd-x-puma-xo-collection-nyc |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224005/https://hypebeast.com/2017/11/he-weeknd-x-puma-xo-collection-nyc |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=Hypebeast}}</ref>

In 2017, Tesfaye partnered with retail company [[H&M]] for their men's collection.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Christian |first=Scott |date=February 2, 2017 |title=The Weeknd and H&M Team Up for the New Spring Icons Collection |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |url=https://www.esquire.com/style/mens-fashion/news/a52793/the-weeknd-hm-spring-icons-collection/}}</ref> He cut ties with the company in 2018, following a racist incident within the company.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yoo |first=Noah |date=January 8, 2018 |title=The Weeknd Cuts Ties With H&M Over "Deeply Offensive" Photo |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-cuts-ties-with-hm-over-deeply-offensive-photo/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224033/https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-cuts-ties-with-hm-over-deeply-offensive-photo/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]}}</ref> In July 2018, Tesfaye collaborated with [[Marvel Comics]] to release a comic book inspired by his third studio album ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Saponara |first=Michael |date=March 23, 2018 |title=Marvel Unveils 'The Weeknd Presents: Starboy' Comic Book Release Date |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8257745/marvel-the-weeknd-starboy-comic-book-release-date |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224057/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8257745/marvel-the-weeknd-starboy-comic-book-release-date |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In August, he released an apparel collection in collaboration with [[A Bathing Ape]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 30, 2018 |title=The Weeknd x BAPE Summer Capsule Collection Dropping August 4 |website=[[Highsnobiety]] |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/the-weeknd-bape-summer-2018-capsule/ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=BAPE® x XO |url=https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/bape-x-xo |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224039/https://us.bape.com/blogs/news/bape-x-xo |archive-date=January 7, 2021 | website=[[A Bathing Ape]]}}</ref> A second collection was released in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stavropoulos |first=Laura |date=January 8, 2020 |title=The Weeknd Reveals Latest XO And BAPE Capsule Collection |website=[[uDiscover Music]] |url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-xo-bape-collection/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224041/https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-xo-bape-collection/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In April 2019, Tesfaye became an owner and global ambassador of the [[esports]] company [[OverActive Media]], who owns the [[Splyce]] and [[Overwatch League]] team [[Toronto Defiant]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=April 10, 2019 |title=The Weeknd signs on as part owner, global ambassador of esports firm |publisher=[[CBC News]] |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/weeknd-overactive-overwatch-1.5091861 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224059/https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/weeknd-overactive-overwatch-1.5091861 |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

On August 31, 2020, Tesfaye partnered with [[TD Canada Trust|TD Bank]] to launch Black HXOUSE, an entrepreneurial initiative within the incubator HXOUSE, where he serves as a [[Partnership#Silent partners|sleeping partner]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=August 31, 2020 |title=The Weeknd Joins With TD Bank to Launch Black Hxouse Entrepreneurship Initiative |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/the-weeknd-td-bank-black-hxouse-entrepreneurship-1234754550/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224036/https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/the-weeknd-td-bank-black-hxouse-entrepreneurship-1234754550/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> On September 9, Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] announced a CA$221,000,000 joint venture with HXOUSE for Black Canadian entrepreneurs.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 9, 2020 |title=Trudeau announces cash for loans, support to Black Canadian entrepreneurs |work=[[CP24]] |url=https://www.cp24.com/news/trudeau-announces-cash-for-loans-support-to-black-canadian-entrepreneurs-1.5098035 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224112/https://www.cp24.com/news/trudeau-announces-cash-for-loans-support-to-black-canadian-entrepreneurs-1.5098035 |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In March 2021, Tesfaye auctioned a collection of visual artwork and an unreleased song in the form of a [[non-fungible token]] (NFT) on [[Nifty Gateway]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Weeknd Teases Upcoming NFT Song|url=https://vman.com/article/the-weeknd-teases-upcoming-nft-song/ |date=March 29, 2021|website=Vman}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Weeknd will sell an unreleased song and visual art via NFT auction|url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/03/31/the-weeknd-nft/ |date=March 31, 2021 |website=TechCrunch |first= Anthony|last= Ha}}</ref> In October, he joined football player [[Tom Brady]]'s NFT platform Autograph as a member of their [[board of directors]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tom Brady Announced Partnership With The Weeknd in the Best Way Possible |url=https://foxsportsradio.iheart.com/content/2021-10-22-tom-brady-announced-partnership-with-the-weeknd-in-the-best-way-possible/ |access-date=March 22, 2022 |website=FOX Sports Radio |language=en}}</ref>

In 2022, Tesfaye invested in plant-based beverage brand [[Koia]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=April 21, 2022|title=Plant-based beverage brand Koia Gets Investments from All-Stars to provide Plant-Based Accessibility For All|url=https://vegworldmag.com/plant-based-beverage-brand-koia-gets-investments-from-all-stars-to-provide-plant-based-accessibility-for-all/|website=VegWorld Magazine|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Philanthropy ==
After being presented with a Bikila Award for Professional Excellence in 2014, Tesfaye donated CA$50,000 to the [[University of Toronto]] to fund a new course on [[Ge'ez]], the classic language of Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carissimo|first=Justin|date=August 7, 2016|title=The Weeknd donates $50,000 to language class at the University of Toronto|work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-the-university-of-toronto-to-help-start-an-ethiopic-studies-program-a7177606.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224216/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/weeknd-donates-50-000-university-toronto-help-start-ethiopic-studies-program-a7177606.html|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In May 2016, during [[Orthodox Easter]], Tesfaye donated CA$50,000 to the St. Mary [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo]] Cathedral in Toronto, Canada, a church he attended growing up.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Min|first=Lilian|date=August 7, 2016|title=The Weeknd donated $50,000 to a cause dear to his heart|work=[[HelloGiggles]]|url=https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/weeknd-donated-50000-cause-dear-heart/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=May 2, 2016|title=The Weeknd Donates $50,000 to St. Mary Ethiopian Orthodox Church in Toronto|url=https://www.ethiosports.com/2016/05/02/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-st-mary-ethiopian-orthodox-church-in-toronto/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218171133/https://www.ethiosports.com/2016/05/02/the-weeknd-donates-50000-to-st-mary-ethiopian-orthodox-church-in-toronto/|archive-date=February 18, 2021}}</ref> In August 2016, he funded a new [[Ethiopian studies]] program at the University of Toronto.<ref name="blm250">{{Cite news|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=August 14, 2016|title=The Weeknd has donated $250,000 to Black Lives Matter|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-6-1194305|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224054/https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-6-1194305|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In June 2017, Tesfaye donated US$100,000 to the Suubi Health Center, a maternity and children's medical facility in Budondo, [[Uganda]]. He was inspired to support the center after learning of [[French Montana]]'s work with [[Global Citizen (organization)|Global Citizen]] and Mama Hope to help raise awareness for Suubi and the people of Uganda.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Malkin|first=Marc|title=The Weeknd Donates $100,000 to Health Center in Uganda|publisher=[[E!]]|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/858296/the-weeknd-donates-100-000-to-health-center-in-uganda|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224216/https://www.eonline.com/news/858296/the-weeknd-donates-100-000-to-health-center-in-uganda|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

In April 2020, Tesfaye launched a line of non-medical [[Face masks during the COVID-19 pandemic|face masks]] with all of the proceeds going to the [[MusiCares COVID-19 Relief Fund]], a campaign launched by [[the Recording Academy]] to help musicians affected by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=April 23, 2020|title=The Weeknd Brings Back XO Face Mask For COVID-19 Relief|website=HYPEBAE|url=https://hypebae.com/2020/4/the-weeknd-face-mask-xo-restock-coronavirus-covid-19-donation-musicares-relief-fund-announcement|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224129/https://hypebae.com/2020/4/the-weeknd-face-mask-xo-restock-coronavirus-covid-19-donation-musicares-relief-fund-announcement|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In addition, Tesfaye donated US$500,000 to [[MusiCares]] and CA$500,000 to the [[Scarborough Health Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=June 29, 2020|title=The Weeknd Donates $1 Million to MusiCares' and His Hometown's Coronavirus Relief|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-donates-1-million-coronavirus-relief-1234693172/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224111/https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-donates-1-million-coronavirus-relief-1234693172/|archive-date=January 7, 2021|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>

In August 2016, Tesfaye donated US$250,000 to the [[Black Lives Matter Global Network Foundation]] following numerous reports of [[police brutality in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Melas|first=Chloe|date=August 11, 2016|title=The Weeknd donates $250,000 to Black Lives Matter|publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/08/11/media/the-weeknd-250000-black-lives-matter/}}</ref><ref name="blm250" /><ref>{{Cite news|date=August 11, 2016|title=The Weeknd gives $250,000 to Black Lives Matter|website=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/11/the-weeknd-black-lives-matter-beyonce-jay-z-drake|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224112/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/11/the-weeknd-black-lives-matter-beyonce-jay-z-drake|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In May 2020, in response to the [[murder of George Floyd]] and the [[George Floyd protests|protests]] that followed, Tesfaye donated US$500,000 to the Black Lives Matter Global Network Foundation, [[Colin Kaepernick]]'s Know Your Rights Camp, and the National Bail Out.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=June 2, 2020|title=The Weeknd Donated $500K to Racial Justice Initiatives: 'Please Give What You Can Even If It's a Small Amount'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9395412/the-weeknd-donated-500k-racial-justice-initiatives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224055/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9395412/the-weeknd-donated-500k-racial-justice-initiatives|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> He then urged other music executives, major record labels, and streaming services to donate to the cause as well.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=June 2, 2020|title=The Weeknd Calls on Major Music Companies to 'Go Big and Public' With Blackout Tuesday Donations|url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/the-weeknd-blackout-tuesday-black-lives-matter-major-labels-donations-1234623619/|access-date=August 3, 2021|website=Variety|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Curto|first=Justin|date=June 3, 2020|title=WMG Creates Vague $100 Million Anti-Racism Fund Following the Weeknd's Criticism|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/06/the-weeknd-blm-record-labels-warner-music-group.html|access-date=August 3, 2021|website=Vulture|language=en-us}}</ref>

On August 7, 2020, Tesfaye held the "Weeknd Experience", an interactive [[virtual concert]] on the social media platform [[TikTok]] that drew two million total viewers, including 275,000 concurrent viewers. The concert raised over US$350,000 for the [[Equal Justice Initiative]]. He also donated US$300,000 to Global Aid for Lebanon in support of victims of the [[2020 Beirut explosion|Beirut explosion]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=August 12, 2020|title=The Weeknd Virtual Concert on TikTok Drew Over 2M Viewers, Raised $350,000 for Equal Justice Initiative|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/the-weeknd-tiktok-virtual-concert-2-million-viewers-1234733104/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224119/https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/the-weeknd-tiktok-virtual-concert-2-million-viewers-1234733104/|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahadevan|first=Tara C.|date=August 12, 2020|title=The Weeknd, TikTok Raise $350K for Equal Justice Initiative, Singer Also Donates $300K to Beirut Explosion Victims|work=[[Complex Networks]]|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/08/the-weeknd-tiktok-raise-350000-equal-justice-initiative-virtual-concert}}</ref> On November 2, the [[University of Toronto]] announced that it was able to reach and surpass its fundraising goal of CA$500,000 for its [[Ethiopic]] program, which included a CA$30,000 donation from Tesfaye.<ref>{{Cite news|date=November 2, 2020|title=With support from The Weeknd, U of T's Ethiopic program soars past $500,000 endowment goal|website=[[University of Toronto]]|url=https://www.utoronto.ca/news/support-weeknd-u-t-s-ethiopic-program-soars-past-500000-endowment-goal|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224120/https://www.utoronto.ca/news/support-weeknd-u-t-s-ethiopic-program-soars-past-500000-endowment-goal|archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In May 2021, he was among the celebrities expressing more solidarity for <!--maintain neutrality--> civilians who died during the [[2021 Israel–Palestine crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Nolan|first=Emma|date=May 11, 2021|title=Bella Hadid, Dua Lipa and the Other Celebs Supporting Palestine Over Israel|url=https://www.newsweek.com/palestine-celebrities-support-conflict-israel-bella-gigi-hadid-mark-ruffalo-dua-lipa-1590420|url-access=limited|website=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=May 11, 2021|title=The Weeknd Shares Instagram Posts Protesting Sheikh Jarrah Eviction|website=[[Haaretz]]|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/the-weekend-shares-instagram-posts-protesting-sheikh-jarrah-eviction-1.9794503}}</ref> On September 23, Tesfaye was honored with the [[Quincy Jones]] Humanitarian Award at the inaugural Music in Action Awards, presented by the Black Music Action Coalition.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Halperin|first1=Shirley|last2=Tangcay|first2=Jazz|date=September 24, 2021|title=The Weeknd, Motown's Ethiopia Habtemariam Highlight Emotional Night at Black Music Action Coalition Awards|url=https://variety.com/2021/music/news/weeknd-black-music-action-coalition-awards-1235073379/|access-date=October 8, 2021|website=Variety|language=en-US}}</ref>

On January 9, 2024, Tesfaye partnered with the non-profit organization [[School on Wheels Inc.]] to support more than 1,000 students experiencing homelessness.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Mamo |first=Heran |date=January 9, 2024 |title=The Weeknd & School on Wheels Team Up to Provide Laptops, Tutoring & Mentorship for Homeless L.A. Students |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-school-on-wheels-laptops-tutoring-mentorship-homeless-students-los-angeles-1235578590/ |access-date=January 9, 2024 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> To coincide with his concert in Brazil, Tesfaye released merchandise and will donate 10% of the net profits to the Brazilian Soul Fund of BrazilFoundation.<ref>{{cite web |title=São Paulo XO Logo Hoodie |url=https://xo.store/products/sao-paulo-xo-logo-hoodie |access-date=September 8, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Weeknd's São Paulo concert: A night to remember |date=August 22, 2024 |url=https://rollingout.com/2024/08/22/the-weeknds-sao-paulo-concert/ |access-date=September 8, 2024}}</ref>

=== WFP ambassadorship ===
On April 4, 2021, Tesfaye announced a US$1,000,000 donation through the [[United Nations]] [[World Food Programme]] (WFP) to relief efforts in [[Ethiopia]] for people affected by the [[Tigray War]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Shafer|first=Ellise|date=April 4, 2021|title=The Weeknd Donates $1 Million to Relief Efforts in Ethiopia|url=https://variety.com/2021/music/news/the-weeknd-1-million-hunger-relief-ethiopia-1234943921/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> On June 9, he met with the administrator of the [[United States Agency for International Development]], [[Samantha Power]], to discuss the humanitarian crisis of the Tigray War.<ref>{{Cite web|date=June 9, 2021|title=USAID Administrator Power Held Urgent Meetings on Famine and Atrocities in Tigray, Ethiopia, including Ministerial Convening with Nine Countries and Conversation with The Weeknd, And Announced $181 Million in New USAID Assistance|url=https://usaid.gov/news-information/press-releases/jun-9-2021-usaid-administrator-power-held-urgent-meetings-famine-atrocities-tigray|access-date=June 10, 2021|website=usaid.gov}}</ref> Tesfaye was appointed as a UN [[Goodwill ambassador|Goodwill Ambassador]] for the World Food Programme on October 7.<ref>{{Cite web|title=It's The Weeknd! Superstar singer becomes World Food Programme Goodwill Ambassador |url=https://www.wfp.org/stories/its-weeknd-superstar-singer-becomes-world-food-programme-goodwill-ambassador|access-date=October 8, 2021|website=www.wfp.org|date=October 8, 2021 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Weeknd Becomes U.N. Goodwill Ambassador for World Food Programme|url=https://www.wfpusa.org/theweeknd/|access-date=October 8, 2021|website=World Food Program USA|language=en-US}}</ref> On March 3, 2022, he partnered with the WFP to launch the XO Humanitarian Fund. Through the fund, Tesfaye was to donate US$1 from every ticket sold at his [[After Hours til Dawn Tour]], in addition to a US$500,000 donation, to the WFP.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=March 3, 2022 |title=The Weeknd Unveils Stadium Tour Dates, Launches XO Humanitarian Fund With Combined $1.5 Million Donation |url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/the-weeknd-stadium-tour-dates-un-world-food-programme-1235195142/ |access-date=March 3, 2022 |website=Variety |language=en-US}}</ref> $2,500,000 from the XO Humanitarian Fund was directed toward WFP's humanitarian response efforts in the [[Gaza Strip]], providing four million emergency meals for those affected by the [[Israeli invasion of the Gaza Strip]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Abby |date=December 1, 2023 |title=The Weeknd Donates $2.5 Million to Gaza Food Deliveries |url=https://consequence.net/2023/12/the-weeknd-donates-emergency-food-deliveries-gaza/ |access-date=December 1, 2023 |website=Consequence of Sound |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cho |first=Regina |date=December 1, 2023 |title=The Weeknd To Provide 4 Million Emergency Meals To Humanitarian Efforts In Gaza |url=https://www.vibe.com/news/entertainment/the-weeknd-provide-4-million-emergency-meals-to-gaza-1234824577/ |access-date=December 1, 2023 |website=Vibe |language=en-US}}</ref> On April 29, 2024, Tesfaye announced he will donate another $2 million to Palestine as loaves of bread.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Weeknd Donates $2 Million to Provide 18 Million Loaves of Bread to Gaza Families |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=April 29, 2024 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-2-million-dollar-donation-gaza-food-aid-1235011969/ |access-date=April 29, 2024}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Tesfaye prefers to keep his personal life out of the public eye.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 3, 2017 |title=Why The Weeknd Wants to Keep an Air of "Mystery" About His Personal Life |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/871163/why-the-weeknd-wants-to-keep-an-air-of-mystery-about-his-personal-life |access-date=May 22, 2022 |website=E! Online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Vanderhoof |first=Erin |date=April 3, 2018 |title=Can the Weeknd Recapture the Mystery? |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/04/can-the-weeknd-recapture-the-mystery |access-date=May 22, 2022 |magazine=Vanity Fair |language=en-US}}</ref> In the beginning of his career, he refrained from participating in interviews and instead chose to communicate via [[Twitter]], which he attributed to shyness and insecurities.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lau |first=Melody |date=July 25, 2011 |title=Mysterious R&B singer sells out first show |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/drake-protege-the-weeknd-proves-hes-no-fluke-in-live-debut-186124/ |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223933/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/drake-protege-the-weeknd-proves-hes-no-fluke-in-live-debut-186124/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> He prefers to be interviewed only in rare situations.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cooper |first=Leonie |date=July 15, 2013 |title=The Weeknd says he's 'boring' in first ever interview |work=[[NME]] |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-58-1257785}}</ref> Tesfaye was raised as an [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox]].<ref name="Fantasy3"/><ref name="Went">{{Cite web |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |date=September 13, 2013 |title=The Weeknd Reveals How He Got His Name... And Where The 'E' Went |publisher=[[MTV News]] |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107223909/http://www.mtv.com/news/1714103/the-weeknd-reddit-ama/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021|mode=cs2}}</ref> When asked whether or not he was still religious, he stated to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' in 2020, "I dunno...everything is a test, and if you are religious or spiritual, you have to go through things."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mamo |first=Heran |title=The Weeknd Says His Song 'Faith' Recalls 'The Darkest Time of My Entire Life' |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9354157/the-weeknd-faith-interview-darkest-time |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211180021/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9354157/the-weeknd-faith-interview-darkest-time |archive-date=February 11, 2021}}</ref>

From April 2015 to August 2019, Tesfaye was in an [[on-again, off-again relationship]] with American model [[Bella Hadid]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lindig |first=Sarah |date=October 10, 2015 |title=Bella Hadid Spends Her Birthday Weekend with the Weeknd |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a31091/bella-hadid-19th-birthday/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011190536/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a31091/bella-hadid-19th-birthday/ |archive-date=October 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=August 6, 2019 |title=Why Bella Hadid and The Weeknd Reportedly Broke Up for the Second Time |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a28625896/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-breakup-2019-reason/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224039/https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a28625896/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-breakup-2019-reason/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> She starred in the music video for his single "[[In the Night (song)|In the Night]]" in December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Weeknd's Super Bloody 'In the Night' Music Video Stars Girlfriend Bella Hadid as a Stripper Assassin |url=https://www.etonline.com/music/177660_the_weeknd_super_bloody_in_the_night_music_video_stars_girlfriend_bella_hadid_as_a_stripper_assassin |access-date=May 22, 2022 |website=www.etonline.com |date=December 8, 2015 |language=en-US}}</ref> He dated American singer-actress [[Selena Gomez]] from January to October 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yagoda |first=Maria |title=Everything We Know About Selena Gomez and The Weeknd's Whirlwind Romance |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |url=https://people.com/music/everything-we-know-selena-gomez-weeknd/ |url-status=live |date=May 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224105/https://people.com/music/everything-we-know-selena-gomez-weeknd/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last1=Chiu | first1=Melody | first2=Char |last2=Adams | title=Selena Gomez and The Weeknd Split After 10 Months Together | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | url=https://people.com/music/selena-gomez-the-weeknd-breakup/ | url-status=live | date=October 30, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224138/https://people.com/music/selena-gomez-the-weeknd-breakup/ | archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> Both of the relationships received widespread media attention, and were the topic of [[Tabloid journalism|tabloid]] speculation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walsh |first=Savannah |date=February 6, 2021 |title=Bella Hadid and The Weeknd's Complete Relationship Timeline, Through Every Breakup and Reconciliation |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a29122950/bella-hadid-the-weeknd-relationship-timeline/ |access-date=May 23, 2022 |website=ELLE |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=January 30, 2017 |title=Why Did Selena Gomez Go Public—And Then Private—With Her Relationship With The Weeknd? |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/selena-gomez-the-weeknd-instagram-official |access-date=May 23, 2022 |website=Vogue |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=A Breakdown of The Weeknd's Most Emo Lyrics About Selena Gomez and Bella Hadid On His New EP |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/the-weeknd-my-dear-melancholy-selena-gomez-bella-hadid |access-date=May 23, 2022 |website=W Magazine |date=March 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Tesfaye has been in a relationship with Saudi-born disc jockey Simi Khadra since February 2022; publications have noted that unlike his previous romances, he has kept his relationship with Khadra private from the press.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lutkin |first1=Aimeé |date=April 16, 2023 |title=All About The Weeknd's Girlfriend Simi Khadra |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a43611543/who-is-simi-khadra-the-weeknd-girlfriend/ |access-date=November 10, 2023 |website=Elle}}</ref>

Tesfaye's hairstyle, which has been described as one of his most recognizable traits, has been claimed to be partly inspired by American artist [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]].<ref name="Fantasy3"/><ref>{{Cite news |last=Leung |first=Andrew |date=February 10, 2016 |title=The Weeknd's Hair: It's More Than an Homage to Basquiat |work=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]] |url=https://www.mic.com/articles/134936/the-weeknd-s-hair-it-s-more-than-an-homage-to-basquiat}}</ref> He began growing it out in 2011 and remarked at how easy it was to maintain with "a hard shampoo every once in a while".<ref name="Fantasy3" /> He cut his hair in 2016, prior to the release of ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=September 22, 2016 |title=5 '80s & '90s Artists Who May Have Inspired The Weeknd's New Haircut |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7518696/80s-90s-artists-inspired-the-weeknd-new-haircut |url-status=live |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224046/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7518696/80s-90s-artists-inspired-the-weeknd-new-haircut |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> On social media, Tesfaye typically suffixed his first name with "xo",<ref name="Hoby2">{{Cite news |last=Hoby |first=Hermione |author-link=Hermione Hoby |date=November 8, 2012 |title=The Weeknd: Sounds and sensibility |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002143549/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/08/the-weeknd-sense-and-sensibility |archive-date=October 2, 2013}}</ref> which is often used as an [[emoticon]] for [[hugs and kisses]].<ref name="Hoby2" /> According to ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'s}} [[Hermione Hoby]], this was his intention, though others believe it was a reference to his recreational use of [[Ecstasy (drug)|ecstasy]] and [[oxycodone]].<ref name="Know2">{{Cite news |last1=Wagstaff |first1=Keith |last2=Swanson |first2=David |date=October 26, 2015 |title=10 Things You Should Know About the Weeknd |website=[[GQ]] |url=https://www.gq.com/story/5-things-you-should-know-about-the-weeknd |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704214239/https://www.gq.com/story/5-things-you-should-know-about-the-weeknd |archive-date=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Why is The Weeknd's crew called 'XO' |publisher=[[Capital Xtra]] |url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/the-weeknd-facts/why-is-his-crew-called-xo/}}</ref> He later altered the handles on his social media to reflect his stage name in preparation for the release of ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dow |first=Gabriele |date=February 21, 2012 |title=The Weeknd is ready for take-off |work=[[The Torch (St. John's University)|The Torch]] |publisher=[[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]] |url=https://www.torchonline.com/culture/arts-culture/2012/02/21/the-weeknd-is-ready-for-take-off/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224119/https://www.torchonline.com/culture/arts-culture/2012/02/21/the-weeknd-is-ready-for-take-off/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref> In August 2021, during a cover story with ''[[GQ]]'', he described himself as being "sober lite", meaning that he has stopped using drugs with the exception of [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]. He also noted that he drinks alcohol occasionally, stating: "I'm not a heavy drinker, as much as I used to be. The romance of drinking isn't there."<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Weeknd says he's 'sober lite' after giving up drugs, except for weed |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/the-weeknd-california-sober-hard-drugs-weed-173803618.html |access-date=August 3, 2021 |website=www.yahoo.com |date=August 2, 2021 |language=en-US |archive-date=August 2, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210802232420/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/the-weeknd-california-sober-hard-drugs-weed-173803618.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2015, Tesfaye was arrested for allegedly punching a police officer in [[Las Vegas]] after being taken into an elevator to break up a fight.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stutz |first=Colin |date=January 12, 2015 |title=The Weeknd Arrested For Punching Las Vegas Police Officer |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6436581/the-weeknd-arrested-for-punching-las-vegas-police-officer |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224117/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6436581/the-weeknd-arrested-for-punching-las-vegas-police-officer |archive-date=January 7, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=October 23, 2015 |title=The Weeknd avoids jail time after punching police officer |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/23/the-weeknd-abel-tesfaye-avoids-jail-time-after-punching-police-officer |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123215917/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/23/the-weeknd-abel-tesfaye-avoids-jail-time-after-punching-police-officer |archive-date=January 23, 2021}}</ref> He pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] and was sentenced to complete fifty hours of [[community service]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 22, 2015 |title=The Weeknd Pleads No Contest To Punching a Cop |url=https://www.tmz.com/2015/10/22/the-weeknd-no-contest-punching-cop/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224114/https://www.tmz.com/2015/10/22/the-weeknd-no-contest-punching-cop/ |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[TMZ]]}}</ref>

As of August 2021, Tesfaye was residing in [[Bel Air, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Clarke |first=Katherine |date=August 19, 2021 |title=The Weeknd Buys $70 Million Mansion in One of L.A.'s Biggest Deals of the Year |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-weeknd-buys-70-million-los-angeles-mansion-11629400904 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230821203607/https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-weeknd-buys-70-million-los-angeles-mansion-11629400904 |archive-date=August 21, 2023 |access-date=November 4, 2021 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 20, 2021 |title=The Weeknd Drops $70 Million on a Massive Bel Air Mansion |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/the-weeknd-buys-bel-air-mansion |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230826143731/https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/the-weeknd-buys-bel-air-mansion |archive-date=August 26, 2023 |access-date=November 4, 2021 |website=Architectural Digest |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2017, he purchased a home in [[Hidden Hills, California]] for $18.5 million, which he sold to [[Madonna]] in 2021 for $19.3 million.<ref>{{Cite news |date=April 12, 2021 |title=Madonna Drops $19.3 Million on The Weeknd's Hidden Hills Estate |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lifestyle/style/madonna-buys-19-3-million-house-from-the-weeknd-4164951/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231023050807/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lifestyle/style/madonna-buys-19-3-million-house-from-the-weeknd-4164951/|archive-date=October 23, 2023|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Tesfaye previously lived in [[Penthouse apartment|penthouses]] in [[Westwood, Los Angeles]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Leitereg |first=Neal J. |date=November 21, 2019 |title=The Weeknd buys a penthouse in Westwood's Beverly West for $21 million |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/real-estate/story/2019-11-21/the-weeknd-buys-penthouse-westwood-beverly-west-for-21-million |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240307025533/https://www.latimes.com/business/real-estate/story/2019-11-21/the-weeknd-buys-penthouse-westwood-beverly-west-for-21-million |url-access=limited |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 7, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.mansionglobal.com/articles/the-weeknd-snaps-up-21-million-los-angeles-penthouse-209605 | title=The Weeknd Snaps Up $21 Million Los Angeles Penthouse | first=Beckie | last=Strum | date=November 22, 2019 | website=[[Mansion Global]]}}</ref> and [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Halberg |first=Morgan |date=May 1, 2020 |title=The Weeknd Isn't Giving Up His Tribeca Penthouse Just Yet |url=https://observer.com/2020/05/the-weeknd-keeps-renting-tribeca-penthouse-renew-lease-coronavirus/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240108135914/https://observer.com/2020/05/the-weeknd-keeps-renting-tribeca-penthouse-renew-lease-coronavirus/ |archive-date=January 8, 2024 |work=[[The New York Observer]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Brandt |first=Libertina |date=March 31, 2022 |title=Home for The Weeknd: How the R&B Superstar Built a Property Portfolio Worth Millions |url=https://www.mansionglobal.com/articles/home-for-the-weeknd-how-the-r-b-superstar-built-a-property-portfolio-worth-millions-01648758019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231023053009/https://www.mansionglobal.com/articles/home-for-the-weeknd-how-the-r-b-superstar-built-a-property-portfolio-worth-millions-01648758019 |archive-date=October 23, 2023 |access-date=April 4, 2022 |website=www.mansionglobal.com |language=en-US |quote=The Weeknd no longer rents the unit, according to a source with knowledge of his holdings.}}</ref>

In April 2023, Tesfaye revealed that he has [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADHD]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=O. Harris |first=Jeremy |date=April 14, 2023 |title=The Weeknd Introduces Us to Abel Tesfaye |url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/the-weeknd-introduces-us-to-abel-tesfaye |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231209110641/https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/the-weeknd-introduces-us-to-abel-tesfaye |archive-date=December 9, 2023 |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]}}</ref>

==Accolades==
{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by the Weeknd}}
Tesfaye has won four [[Grammy Awards]], a [[Latin Grammy Awards|Latin Grammy Award]], twenty [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], six [[American Music Award]]s, three [[MTV Video Music Awards]] and twenty-two [[Juno Award]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bell |first=David |title=The Weeknd really cleaned up this Juno Awards weekend |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/junos-sunday-night-1.3517082 |url-status=live |date=April 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107224133/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/junos-sunday-night-1.3517082 |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> He has also received nominations for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] and a [[Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Award]].<ref name="grammy2">{{Cite web|title=The Weeknd|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/weeknd/18167|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419192514/https://www.grammy.com/artist/the-weeknd|archive-date=April 19, 2017|publisher=[[Grammy Awards]]}}</ref>

In October 2014, Tesfaye was awarded the [[Allan Slaight]] Honour by [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] for "making a positive impact in the fields of music, film, literature, visual or performing arts, sports, innovation or philanthropy".<ref name="slaight">{{Cite press release |title=The Weeknd honoured with Allan Slaight Award from Canada's Walk of Fame |date=February 14, 2015 |publisher=[[Canada's Walk of Fame]] |via=[[Cision]] |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame-515623821.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214052542/http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/story/the-weeknd-honoured-with-allan-slaight-award-from-canadas-walk-of-fame |archive-date=February 14, 2015}}</ref>

[[Toronto]] mayor [[John Tory]] announced that the city would observe February 7, 2021, as the Weeknd Day to commemorate Tesfaye's [[Super Bowl LV halftime show|Super Bowl halftime performance]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Peters|first=Mitchell|date=February 7, 2021|title=Toronto Declares 'The Weeknd Day' to Honor Singer's Super Bowl Performance|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/toronto-the-weeknd-day-super-bowl-9522634/|access-date=December 3, 2021|magazine=Billboard|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=February 7, 2021|title=The Weeknd has been given his own day by Toronto mayor|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-given-own-day-toronto-mayor-2874646|access-date=December 3, 2021|website=NME|language=en-GB}}</ref>

